{"key":"processedPost-10657097","value":{"id":10657097,"first":10656072,"last":10657114,"when":1247326102,"utime":"07/11/09 06:28 PM","content":"Light isn't a pinning trigger during colonization so there's no need or reason to keep them in the dark.&nbsp; That's old, inaccurate info from many years ago.<br /><br />I suspect that due to improperly incubating them, the temp got too high and stimulated thermophilic bacteria to grow, thus it took over half your substrate.&nbsp; When the mycelium ran up against the contamination, it sensed full colonization of the <i>available</i> substate, and started to pin as a survival mechanism.&nbsp; Cubes will pin in total darkness.<br /><br />You should colonize at normal room temperature for best results and lowest contamination rate.<br />RR","title":"Re: Pinning in my colonizing bag....","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}